Telco Customer Churn¶

Dataset sourced from: https://www.kaggle.com/blastchar/telco-customer-churn

This dataset contains details about the telecom company, Telco's customers where each row represents one customer. My aim is to predict whether the customer will leave or not, while also trying to unearth patterns in what type of customers tend to churn.

Features:¶

gender: M or F
SeniorCitizen: Whether customer is senior citizen or not
Partner : Whether customer has a partner or not
Dependents : Whether customer has dependents or not
tenure : How long the customer was with the company, in months
PhoneService : Whether customer has phone line or not
MultipleLines : Whether customer has multiple phone lines or not
InternetService : Type of internet service provided: DSL, FIber or no internet
OnlineSecurity : Whethere customer has availed this additonal service
OnlineBackup : Whethere customer has availed this additonal service
DeviceProtection : Whethere customer has availed this additonal service
TechSupport : Whethere customer has availed this additonal service
StreamingTV : Whethere customer has availed this additonal service
StreamingMovies : Whethere customer has availed this additonal service
Contract : Whether customer's contract is month to month or yearly
PaperlessBilling : Yes or No
PaymentMethod : Method of payment used by customer
MonthlyCharges : Charges in dollars
TotalCharges : Total charges(monhtly * tenure)
Churn : Yes or No

Data Cleaning¶

All the categorical features are one hot encoded. The 'No' column of binary features are droppped.

In [324]:
del data['customerID']
data = pd.get_dummies(data)
drop = ['Churn_No', 'gender_Female', 'Partner_No', 'Dependents_No', 'PhoneService_No', 'PaperlessBilling_No']
data = data.drop(drop,axis=1)

y = data.iloc[:,40]
del data['Churn_Yes']
X = data

Feature Importance¶

Random forest classifier is used to find the feature importances. The feature with less than the median imprtance are dropped

In [325]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectFromModel
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold

classr = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=5000, n_jobs=4, max_depth=8)
classr = classr.fit(X, y)

features = pd.DataFrame()
features['features'] = X.columns
features['importance'] = classr.feature_importances_
sortf = features.sort_values(by = ['importance'], ascending = False)
In [326]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,12))
plt.title("Feature Importance")
ax = sns.barplot(x='importance', y='features', data=sortf, palette="rocket", orient='h')
In [327]:
select_feat = SelectFromModel(classr, threshold = 'median', prefit = True)
X = select_feat.transform(X)
In [328]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.3, random_state = 0)

Modeling¶

Grid Search is used to find the best hyperparameters for the random forest classifier:

Best parameters: 'criterion': 'entropy', 'max_depth': 8, 'max_features': 'log2', 'n_estimators': 40
Accuracy: 80.2%
True Positives: 1413
False Positives: 147
True Negatives: 287
False Negatives: 266
True Positive Rate: 0.84
False Positive Rate: 0.33
Precision: 0.91

Cross validation is used to check for over fitting, mean accuracy is around 80% with a std deviation of 0.01

In [222]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

params = {
        'n_estimators' : [50, 40, 30],
        'criterion' : ['entropy', 'gini'],
        'max_features' : ['sqrt', 'log2', None],
        'max_depth' : [8, 9, 10]
          }

crv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits = 5)
grids = GridSearchCV(classr, params, scoring = 'accuracy', cv = crv, n_jobs = -1)
grids = grids.fit(X_train, y_train)

ROC Curve¶

In [332]:
pred = probs[:,1]
fpr, tpr, threshold = roc_curve(y_test, pred)
roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)


plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic')
